th of political rhetoric, newspaper coverage, textbooks, and more, Colin McCullough outlines continuity and change in the production and reception of messages about peacekeeping. He demonstrates that those who produced messages about peacekeeping often overlooked the particularities of individual missions, preferring to link their cultural products to political discourses about national identity. Engaging in debates about Canada’s international standing, as well as its broader national character, this book is a welcome addition to the history of Canada’s changing national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational characteristics, CanadianxHistoriography. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian, in literature. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian. 0aNational interestzCanadaxHistory. 0aPeace-building, CanadianxPublic opinion. 0aPeace-building, CanadianzCanadaxPublic opinionxHistory. 0aPeace-building, Canadian, in literature. 0aPeace-building, Canadian, in motion pictures. 0aPeacekeeping forces, CanadianxHistoriography. 0aPeacekeeping forces, CanadianxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311141795040uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483250240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774832502423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774832502/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-141795-0  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGB